(Men chanting) Fresh fish!

256
00:18:02,749 --> 00:18:04,416
(Door opens)

257
00:18:04,500 --> 00:18:07,294
What the Christ is this happy horse shit?

258
00:18:07,378 --> 00:18:10,088
He took the Lord's name in vain.
I'm telling the Warden.

259
00:18:10,173 --> 00:18:11,673
With my baton up your ass!

260
00:18:11,758 --> 00:18:13,425
FAT ASS: Let me out of here!

261
00:18:13,509 --> 00:18:16,887
What is your malfunction,
you fat barrel of monkey spunk?

262
00:18:16,971 --> 00:18:18,138
FAT ASS: Please...

263
00:18:18,222 --> 00:18:20,265
I ain't supposed to be here.

264
00:18:20,349 --> 00:18:21,725
Not me!

265
00:18:21,809 --> 00:18:24,269
I ain't gonna count to three, or even one.

266
00:18:24,353 --> 00:18:26,646
Shut the fuck up, or I'll sing you a lullaby!

267
00:18:26,731 --> 00:18:28,565
(Whispers) Shut up, man. Shut up.

268
00:18:28,649 --> 00:18:29,941
There's been a mistake!

269
00:18:30,026 --> 00:18:33,195
You don't understand.
I'm not supposed to be here!

270
00:18:33,279 --> 00:18:34,362
Open that cell.

271
00:18:34,447 --> 00:18:38,575
MAN: Me neither.
You people run this place like a fucking prison!

272
00:18:46,083 --> 00:18:48,126
HADLEY: Son of a bitch.

273
00:18:48,211 --> 00:18:50,086
(Thuds)

274
00:18:50,171 --> 00:18:52,214
(Whimpering)

275
00:18:52,298 --> 00:18:54,341
PRISONER: Take it easy.

276
00:18:59,722 --> 00:19:01,348
(Yelps)

277
00:19:17,156 --> 00:19:20,534
If I hear so much as a mouse fart in here
the rest of the night,

278
00:19:20,618 --> 00:19:24,287
I swear by God and sonny Jesus,
you will all visit the infirmary.

279
00:19:24,372 --> 00:19:26,414
Every last motherfucker in here.

280
00:19:30,378 --> 00:19:34,005
Call the trustees.
Take that tub of shit down to the infirmary.

281
00:19:48,354 --> 00:19:53,066
RED: His first night in the joint,
Andy Dufresne cost me two packs of cigarettes.

282
00:19:53,150 --> 00:19:55,986
He never made a sound.

283
00:19:58,906 --> 00:20:00,949
(Gate buzzer)

284
00:20:11,544 --> 00:20:14,796
GUARD: Tier 3 North. Clear.

285
00:20:14,881 --> 00:20:17,048
Tier 2 South. Clear.

286
00:20:17,133 --> 00:20:19,009
Tier 3 South. Clear.

287
00:20:19,093 --> 00:20:21,052
Tier 1 North...

288
00:20:21,137 --> 00:20:23,930
- Tier 1 South. Clear.
- Tier 4 South. Clear.

289
00:20:24,015 --> 00:20:26,057
Prepare to roll out.

290
00:20:29,478 --> 00:20:31,521
GUARD: Roll out!

291
00:21:24,450 --> 00:21:27,243
Are... Are you going to eat that?

292
00:21:27,328 --> 00:21:30,205
I hadn't... I hadn't planned on it.

293
00:21:31,499 --> 00:21:32,499
Do you mind?

294
00:21:39,882 --> 00:21:42,467
Ah...that's nice and ripe.

295
00:21:47,264 --> 00:21:49,307
(Chirps)

296
00:21:54,105 --> 00:21:56,564
Jake says thank you.

297
00:21:56,649 --> 00:21:59,025
Fell out of his nest over by the plate shop.

298
00:22:01,320 --> 00:22:05,865
I'm going to look after him
until he's big enough to fly.

299
00:22:05,950 --> 00:22:07,701
Oh, no, no. Here he comes.

300
00:22:10,871 --> 00:22:14,791
Morning, fellas. Fine morning, ain't it?

301
00:22:14,875 --> 00:22:17,293
You know why it's a fine morning, don't you?

302
00:22:17,378 --> 00:22:19,796
Come on. Set 'em down.
I want 'em all lined up here,

303
00:22:19,880 --> 00:22:22,674
just like a pretty little chorus line.

304
00:22:22,758 --> 00:22:24,843
Yeah, look at that!

305
00:22:24,927 --> 00:22:27,804
- Look at that. Oh, Lord!
- I can't stand this guy.

306
00:22:27,888 --> 00:22:28,930
(Inhales)

307
00:22:29,015 --> 00:22:31,683
Yes. Richmond, Virginia.

308
00:22:31,767 --> 00:22:33,852
- Smell my ass!
- After he smells mine.

309
00:22:33,936 --> 00:22:39,274
Gee, Red, it was a terrible shame
about your horse coming in last, an' all.

310
00:22:39,358 --> 00:22:42,569
But I sure do love that winning horse of mine,
though.

311
00:22:42,653 --> 00:22:45,363
I owe that boy a great big, sloppy kiss
when I see him.

312
00:22:45,448 --> 00:22:48,450
Why don't you give him some of your cigarettes,
instead?

313
00:22:48,534 --> 00:22:50,326
Lucky fuck.

314
00:22:50,411 --> 00:22:52,120
Hey, Tyrell.

315
00:22:52,204 --> 00:22:55,165
You pull infirmary duty this week?

316
00:22:55,249 --> 00:22:56,958
How's that horse of mine doing?

317
00:22:57,043 --> 00:22:58,501
Dead.

318
00:22:58,586 --> 00:23:03,923
Hadley busted his head up pretty good.
The doc had already gone home for the night.

319
00:23:04,008 --> 00:23:06,718
Poor bastard lay there till this morning.

320
00:23:06,802 --> 00:23:09,596
By then, hell, there weren't nothing we could do.

321
00:23:15,478 --> 00:23:16,978
What was his name?

322
00:23:20,274 --> 00:23:21,608
What did you say?

323
00:23:23,527 --> 00:23:25,904
I was just wondering if anyone knew his name.

324
00:23:25,988 --> 00:23:28,656
What the fuck do you care, new fish?

325
00:23:30,159 --> 00:23:33,495
It doesn't fuckin' matter what his name was.
He's dead.

326
00:23:52,890 --> 00:23:55,225
Hey...

327
00:23:55,309 --> 00:23:58,019
Anybody come at you yet?

328
00:23:59,563 --> 00:24:01,523
Anybody get to you yet?

329
00:24:02,691 --> 00:24:05,735
Hey, we all need friends in here.

330
00:24:05,820 --> 00:24:07,695
I could be a friend to you.

331
00:24:10,199 --> 00:24:11,825
Hey...

332
00:24:16,705 --> 00:24:18,540
Hard to get.

333
00:24:20,251 --> 00:24:21,876
I like that.

334
00:24:28,551 --> 00:24:31,845
RED: Andy kept pretty much to himself at first.

335
00:24:31,929 --> 00:24:34,389
I guess he had a lot on his mind,

336
00:24:34,473 --> 00:24:36,641
trying to adapt to life on the inside.

337
00:24:38,227 --> 00:24:40,937
It wasn't until a month went by
that he opened his mouth

338
00:24:41,021 --> 00:24:43,273
to say more than two words to somebody.

339
00:24:45,234 --> 00:24:47,277
As it turned out...

340
00:24:47,361 --> 00:24:49,237
that somebody was me.

341
00:24:52,867 --> 00:24:56,995
TANNOY: Officers Russell and Burwell
report to the duty officer.

342
00:24:58,080 --> 00:25:00,832
I'm Andy Dufresne.

343
00:25:00,916 --> 00:25:02,959
The wife-killing banker.

344
00:25:04,837 --> 00:25:06,546
Why did you do it?

345
00:25:06,630 --> 00:25:08,256
I didn't, since you ask.

346
00:25:08,340 --> 00:25:11,384
(Laughs) You're gonna fit right in!

347
00:25:11,468 --> 00:25:14,637
Everybody in here's innocent.
Didn't you know that?

348
00:25:14,722 --> 00:25:18,016
- Heywood, what are you in here for?
- Didn't do it. Lawyer fucked me.

349
00:25:20,978 --> 00:25:23,771
Rumour has it you're a real cold fish.

350
00:25:23,856 --> 00:25:27,609
You think your shit smells sweeter than most.
Is that right?

351
00:25:27,693 --> 00:25:30,028
- What do you think?
- To tell you the truth,

352
00:25:30,112 --> 00:25:33,198
I haven't made up my mind. (Chuckles)

353
00:25:33,282 --> 00:25:37,368
I understand
you're a man that knows how to get things.

354
00:25:37,453 --> 00:25:40,955
I'm known to locate certain things,
from time to time.

355
00:25:41,040 --> 00:25:44,042
- I wonder if you might get me a rock hammer.
- A what?

356
00:25:44,126 --> 00:25:45,501
A rock hammer.

357
00:25:45,586 --> 00:25:47,837
- What is it, and why?
- What do you care?

358
00:25:49,757 --> 00:25:52,634
Well, if it was a toothbrush, I'd just quote a price,

359
00:25:52,718 --> 00:25:55,261
but then a toothbrush is a non-lethal object.

360
00:25:56,722 --> 00:25:58,431
Fair enough.

361
00:25:58,515 --> 00:26:00,975
A rock hammer
is about six or seven inches long.

362
00:26:01,060 --> 00:26:02,685
Looks like a miniature pickaxe.

363
00:26:02,770 --> 00:26:03,895
Pickaxe?

364
00:26:03,979 --> 00:26:06,022
- For rocks.
- Rocks.

365
00:26:07,733 --> 00:26:09,901
Quartz?

366
00:26:09,985 --> 00:26:11,611
Quartz.

367
00:26:12,905 --> 00:26:15,281
And some mica.

368
00:26:15,366 --> 00:26:16,491
Shale.

369
00:26:17,618 --> 00:26:19,202
Limestone.

370
00:26:19,286 --> 00:26:21,204
So?

371
00:26:21,288 --> 00:26:23,373
So, I'm a rock hound.

372
00:26:23,457 --> 00:26:26,668
At least, I was in my old life.
I'd like to be again on a limited basis.

373
00:26:26,752 --> 00:26:28,878
Or maybe you want
to hammer somebody's skull.

374
00:26:28,963 --> 00:26:30,421
No, sir.

375
00:26:31,548 --> 00:26:33,132
I have no enemies here.

376
00:26:33,217 --> 00:26:35,551
No? Wait a while.

377
00:26:37,137 --> 00:26:39,305
Word gets around.

378
00:26:39,390 --> 00:26:42,517
The Sisters have taken quite a liking to you.

379
00:26:42,601 --> 00:26:44,352
Especially Bogs.

380
00:26:45,479 --> 00:26:49,691
I don't suppose it would help any
if I explained to them I'm not homosexual.

381
00:26:49,775 --> 00:26:51,276
RED: Neither are they.

382
00:26:51,360 --> 00:26:54,028
You have to be human first. They don't qualify.

383
00:26:59,326 --> 00:27:03,871
Bull queers take by force.
It's all they want or understand.

384
00:27:03,956 --> 00:27:07,583
If I were you,
I'd grow eyes in the back of my head.

385
00:27:07,668 --> 00:27:09,002
Thanks for the advice.

386
00:27:09,086 --> 00:27:10,670
Well, that's free.

387
00:27:10,754 --> 00:27:13,006
You understand my concern.

388
00:27:13,090 --> 00:27:15,633
Well, if there's any trouble,
I won't use the hammer.

389
00:27:15,718 --> 00:27:19,887
Then I guess you want to escape.
Tunnel under the wall, maybe.

390
00:27:21,390 --> 00:27:23,182
Did I miss something? What's funny?

391
00:27:23,267 --> 00:27:26,269
You'll understand
when you see the rock hammer.

392
00:27:28,188 --> 00:27:30,189
What's an item like this usually go for?

393
00:27:30,274 --> 00:27:33,318
Seven dollars in any rock and gem shop.

394
00:27:33,402 --> 00:27:36,070
My normal mark-up's 20 per cent.

395
00:27:36,155 --> 00:27:38,656
But this is a specialty item.

396
00:27:38,741 --> 00:27:41,284
The risk goes up, the price goes up.

397
00:27:41,368 --> 00:27:43,286
Let's make it an even ten bucks.

398
00:27:43,370 --> 00:27:45,204
Ten it is.

399
00:27:46,332 --> 00:27:48,750
Waste of money, if you ask me.

400
00:27:48,834 --> 00:27:50,335
Why's that?

401
00:27:51,462 --> 00:27:54,464
Folks around this joint love surprise inspections.

402
00:27:56,091 --> 00:27:58,384
If they find it, you're gonna lose it.

403
00:27:58,469 --> 00:28:00,595
If they do catch you with it, you don't know me.

404
00:28:00,679 --> 00:28:02,889
Mention my name, we never do business again.

405
00:28:02,973 --> 00:28:06,059
Not for shoelaces or a stick of gum.
Now, you got that?

406
00:28:07,603 --> 00:28:09,020
I understand.

407
00:28:09,104 --> 00:28:10,480
Thank you...

408
00:28:10,564 --> 00:28:12,148
Mr er...?

409
00:28:12,232 --> 00:28:14,650
Red. The name's Red.

410
00:28:14,735 --> 00:28:15,735
Red?

411
00:28:15,819 --> 00:28:18,529
Why do they call you that?

412
00:28:22,242 --> 00:28:24,285
Maybe it's because I'm Irish.

413
00:28:32,294 --> 00:28:35,338
RED: I could see
why some of the boys took him for snobby.

414
00:28:35,422 --> 00:28:38,841
He had a quiet way about him.

415
00:28:38,926 --> 00:28:43,388
A walk and a talk
that just wasn't normal around here.

416
00:28:43,472 --> 00:28:45,014
He strolled...

417
00:28:45,099 --> 00:28:49,435
like a man in a park,
without a care or worry in the world.

418
00:28:49,520 --> 00:28:54,232
Like he had on an invisible coat
that would shield him from this place.

419
00:28:54,316 --> 00:28:58,444
Yeah. I think it would be fair to say...

420
00:28:58,529 --> 00:29:00,571
I liked Andy from the start.

421
00:29:02,324 --> 00:29:05,493
Let's go!
Some of us have got a schedule to keep.

422
00:29:08,831 --> 00:29:10,873
Move it! Come on. Move it!

423
00:29:14,545 --> 00:29:17,630
Bob, how are you doing?
How's the wife treating you?

424
00:29:27,391 --> 00:29:28,850
Easy.

425
00:29:28,934 --> 00:29:30,977
Keep it moving.

426
00:29:33,814 --> 00:29:35,022
Red...

427
00:29:55,586 --> 00:29:59,797
RED: Andy was right. I finally got the joke.

428
00:29:59,882 --> 00:30:04,343
It would take a man about 600 years
to tunnel under the wall with one of these.

429
00:30:08,724 --> 00:30:09,849
Book?

430
00:30:09,933 --> 00:30:11,767
Not today.

431
00:30:17,149 --> 00:30:19,192
- Book?
- No.

432
00:30:21,028 --> 00:30:22,195
Hey, Brooksy.

433
00:30:25,532 --> 00:30:27,575
Delivery for Dufresne.

434
00:30:34,708 --> 00:30:40,296
Book?

435
00:30:43,342 --> 00:30:45,468
Dufresne...

436
00:30:45,552 --> 00:30:47,678
Here's your book.

437
00:30:52,142 --> 00:30:53,768
Thanks.

438
00:30:57,648 --> 00:31:00,858
Dufresne! We're running low on Hexlite.

439
00:31:00,943 --> 00:31:02,985
Get on back and fetch us up some.

440
00:31:40,232 --> 00:31:42,191
If you get this in your eyes, it blinds you.

441
00:31:42,276 --> 00:31:44,986
Honey...hush.

442
00:31:52,119 --> 00:31:53,953
(Groans)

443
00:31:57,082 --> 00:31:59,500
That's it. You fight.

444
00:31:59,585 --> 00:32:01,168
It's better that way.

445
00:32:01,253 --> 00:32:03,004
(Screaming and yelling)

446
00:32:09,595 --> 00:32:12,430
RED: I wish I could tell you
that Andy fought the good fight,

447
00:32:12,514 --> 00:32:15,057
and the Sisters let him be.

448
00:32:15,142 --> 00:32:17,143
I wish I could tell you that.

449
00:32:17,227 --> 00:32:19,270
But prison is no fairy-tale world.

450
00:32:21,273 --> 00:32:23,399
He never said who did it.

451
00:32:23,483 --> 00:32:26,527
But we all knew.

452
00:32:26,612 --> 00:32:28,446
(Gate buzzer)

453
00:32:29,865 --> 00:32:32,742
Things went on like that for a while.

454
00:32:32,826 --> 00:32:35,453
Prison life consists of routine...

455
00:32:35,537 --> 00:32:37,705
and then more routine.

456
00:32:40,125 --> 00:32:43,919
Every so often,
Andy would show up with fresh bruises.

457
00:32:45,130 --> 00:32:47,173
The Sisters kept at him.

458
00:32:47,257 --> 00:32:51,385
Sometimes he was able to fight 'em off.
Sometimes not.

459
00:32:51,470 --> 00:32:54,722
And that's how it went for Andy.

460
00:32:54,806 --> 00:32:57,350
That was his routine.

461
00:32:57,434 --> 00:33:01,228
I do believe
those first two years were the worst for him.

462
00:33:01,313 --> 00:33:03,564
And I also believe,

463
00:33:03,649 --> 00:33:08,194
if things had gone on that way,
this place would have got the best of him.

464
00:33:08,278 --> 00:33:11,238
But then, in the spring of 1949,

465
00:33:11,323 --> 00:33:13,324
the powers that be decided that...

466
00:33:13,408 --> 00:33:16,827
The roof of the licence-plate factory
needs resurfacing.

467
00:33:16,912 --> 00:33:19,622
I need a dozen volunteers for a week's work.

468
00:33:20,832 --> 00:33:22,958
As you know,

469
00:33:23,043 --> 00:33:26,754
special detail carries with it special privileges.

470
00:33:26,838 --> 00:33:28,881
RED: It was outdoor detail...

471
00:33:30,425 --> 00:33:34,011
..and May is one damn fine month
to be working outdoors.

472
00:33:34,096 --> 00:33:35,721
Stay in line there.

473
00:33:35,806 --> 00:33:38,683
More than a hundred men
volunteered for the job.

474
00:33:40,227 --> 00:33:41,852
(Whispers)

475
00:33:43,105 --> 00:33:45,356
Wallace E Unger.

476
00:33:46,566 --> 00:33:49,026
Ellis Redding.

477
00:33:49,111 --> 00:33:51,946
Wouldn't you know it?

478
00:33:52,030 --> 00:33:54,615
Me and some fellows I know
were among the names.

479
00:33:54,700 --> 00:33:56,784
GUARD: Andrew Dufresne.

480
00:33:56,868 --> 00:34:00,413
RED: It only cost us a pack of smokes per man.

481
00:34:00,497 --> 00:34:03,207
I made my usual 20 per cent, of course.

482
00:34:03,291 --> 00:34:06,877
HADLEY: So, this big-shot lawyer
calls me long-distance from Texas.

483
00:34:06,962 --> 00:34:08,671
I say, "Yeah?"

484
00:34:08,755 --> 00:34:12,466
He says, "Sorry to inform you,
but your brother just died."

485
00:34:12,551 --> 00:34:15,052
Oh, damn, Byron. I'm sorry to hear that.

486
00:34:15,137 --> 00:34:16,512
I'm not. He was an asshole.

487
00:34:16,596 --> 00:34:18,931
Ran off years ago.
Figured him for dead, anyway.

488
00:34:19,015 --> 00:34:22,977
So, anyway, this lawyer fella says to me,
"Your brother died a rich man."

489
00:34:23,061 --> 00:34:25,771
Oil wells and shit. Close to a million bucks.

490
00:34:25,856 --> 00:34:28,315
GUARD: A million bucks?

491
00:34:28,400 --> 00:34:30,776
Fucking incredible
how lucky some assholes get.

492
00:34:30,861 --> 00:34:33,404
Jeez-Louise! Are you gonna see any of that?

493
00:34:33,488 --> 00:34:36,574
35,000. That's what he left me.

494
00:34:36,658 --> 00:34:38,576
- Dollars?
- Yeah.

495
00:34:38,660 --> 00:34:41,787
Holy shit! That's great.
That's like winning the sweepstakes.

496
00:34:41,872 --> 00:34:43,080
Isn't it?

497
00:34:43,165 --> 00:34:46,208
Dumb shit. What do you think
the government's gonna do to me?

498
00:34:46,293 --> 00:34:48,794
Take a big, wet bite out of my ass, is what.

499
00:34:48,879 --> 00:34:53,007
Poor Byron! Terrible fucking luck, huh?

500
00:34:53,091 --> 00:34:55,760
RED: Crying shame.

501
00:34:55,844 --> 00:34:57,511
Some people really got it awful!

502
00:34:57,596 --> 00:34:59,138
Andy, are you nuts?

503
00:34:59,222 --> 00:35:01,307
Keep your eyes on your mop, man. Andy!

504
00:35:01,391 --> 00:35:04,393
GUARD: Well, you'll pay some tax,
but you'll still end up...

505
00:35:04,478 --> 00:35:07,313
Oh, yeah, yeah.
Maybe enough to buy a new car. Then what?

506
00:35:07,397 --> 00:35:09,774
I've got to pay tax on the car.

507
00:35:09,858 --> 00:35:13,736
Repair, maintenance, goddamn kids
pestering me to take them for a ride...

508
00:35:13,820 --> 00:35:17,740
And at the end of the year, you figure the tax
wrong, you pay them out of your own pocket.

509
00:35:17,824 --> 00:35:19,992
I tell you...Uncle Sam!

510
