I load up the cart and make my round.

764
00:52:47,039 --> 00:52:50,166
I enter the names on this clipboard here.

765
00:52:50,251 --> 00:52:53,711
Easy-peasy, Japanesey. Any questions?

766
00:52:53,796 --> 00:52:56,756
Brooks, how long have you been librarian?

767
00:52:56,841 --> 00:53:02,011
Oh...I come here in '05,
and they made me librarian in 1912.

768
00:53:02,096 --> 00:53:05,473
And in all that time,
have you ever had an assistant?

769
00:53:05,558 --> 00:53:08,142
No. No, not much to it, really.

770
00:53:08,227 --> 00:53:10,144
Well, why me? Why now?

771
00:53:10,229 --> 00:53:11,729
I don't know,

772
00:53:11,814 --> 00:53:15,108
but it'll be nice to have some company
down here for a change.

773
00:53:15,192 --> 00:53:17,193
HADLEY: Dufresne!

774
00:53:26,537 --> 00:53:28,580
That's him. That's the one.

775
00:53:36,171 --> 00:53:37,463
I'm Dekins.

776
00:53:37,548 --> 00:53:39,966
(Nervously) I was er...

777
00:53:40,092 --> 00:53:44,053
thinking about maybe setting up
some kind of trust fund for my kids' educations.

778
00:53:46,432 --> 00:53:47,891
Oh...

779
00:53:47,975 --> 00:53:49,601
I see.

780
00:53:51,103 --> 00:53:52,937
Well, erm...

781
00:53:54,356 --> 00:53:55,899
..why don't we have a seat,

782
00:53:55,983 --> 00:53:58,026
and talk it over?

783
00:54:00,613 --> 00:54:03,489
Brooks,
do you have a piece of paper and a pencil?

784
00:54:15,002 --> 00:54:16,711
Thanks.

785
00:54:16,795 --> 00:54:18,421
So...

786
00:54:19,715 --> 00:54:22,216
Mr Dekins...

787
00:54:22,301 --> 00:54:26,763
And then Andy says to Mr Dekins,
"Do you want your sons to go to Harvard,

788
00:54:26,847 --> 00:54:28,973
- or Yale?"
- He didn't say that?

789
00:54:29,058 --> 00:54:31,726
As God is my witness, he did!

790
00:54:31,810 --> 00:54:35,188
Dekins just blinked for a second.
Then he laughed himself silly.

791
00:54:35,272 --> 00:54:37,148
And afterwards he shook Andy's hand.

792
00:54:37,232 --> 00:54:38,608
My ass!

793
00:54:38,692 --> 00:54:39,901
Shook his hand.

794
00:54:39,985 --> 00:54:42,946
Hell, I...I near soiled myself! (Laughs)

795
00:54:43,030 --> 00:54:47,241
All Andy needed was a suit and a tie
and a little jiggly hula girl on his desk,

796
00:54:47,326 --> 00:54:48,660
and he would have been:

797
00:54:48,744 --> 00:54:50,286
"Mr Dufresne, if you please"!

798
00:54:50,371 --> 00:54:52,080
Making a few friends, Andy?

799
00:54:53,207 --> 00:54:55,124
I wouldn't say "friends".

800
00:54:55,209 --> 00:54:59,212
I'm a convicted murderer
who provides sound financial planning.

801
00:54:59,296 --> 00:55:01,631
It's a wonderful pet to have.

802
00:55:01,715 --> 00:55:03,633
Got you out of the laundry, though.

803
00:55:03,717 --> 00:55:05,927
Well, it might do more than that.

804
00:55:06,011 --> 00:55:09,013
How about expanding the library?
Get some new books in there.

805
00:55:09,098 --> 00:55:11,808
If you're gonna ask for something,
ask for a pool table.

806
00:55:11,892 --> 00:55:14,352
- Right.
- How do you expect to do that?

807
00:55:14,436 --> 00:55:19,691
I mean, get new books in here,
Mr Dufresne, if you please?

808
00:55:19,775 --> 00:55:21,526
Ask the Warden for funds.

809
00:55:21,610 --> 00:55:22,860
(Laughter)

810
00:55:22,945 --> 00:55:26,239
Son, son. Six wardens
have been through here in my tenure,

811
00:55:26,323 --> 00:55:29,951
and I've learned one immutable, universal truth.

812
00:55:30,035 --> 00:55:31,703
Not one of them born...

813
00:55:31,787 --> 00:55:36,708
whose asshole wouldn't pucker up tighter than
a snare drum when you asked them for funds.

814
00:55:36,792 --> 00:55:39,085
The budget's stretched thin, as it is.

815
00:55:39,169 --> 00:55:40,420
I see.

816
00:55:40,504 --> 00:55:44,007
Perhaps I could write to the State Senate
and request funds from them.

817
00:55:44,133 --> 00:55:48,511
As far as they're concerned, there's only three
ways to spend money when it comes to prisons:

818
00:55:48,595 --> 00:55:50,680
more walls, more bars and more guards.

819
00:55:50,764 --> 00:55:55,184
Still, I'd like to try, with your permission.
A letter a week. They can't ignore me for ever.

820
00:55:55,269 --> 00:55:56,811
Sure can.

821
00:55:56,895 --> 00:55:59,772
But you write your letters, if it makes you happy.

822
00:55:59,857 --> 00:56:02,108
I'll even mail them for you. How's that?

823
00:56:04,069 --> 00:56:07,113
RED: So, Andy started writing a letter a week,

824
00:56:07,197 --> 00:56:09,282
just like he said.

825
00:56:13,328 --> 00:56:17,415
And, just like Norton said, Andy got no answers.

826
00:56:25,299 --> 00:56:30,803
The following April, Andy did tax returns
for half the guards at Shawshank.

827
00:56:30,888 --> 00:56:33,973
The year after that, he did them all...

828
00:56:34,058 --> 00:56:36,100
including the Warden's.

829
00:56:37,519 --> 00:56:41,272
The year after that, they rescheduled
the start of the intramural season

830
00:56:41,356 --> 00:56:43,399
to coincide with tax season.

831
00:56:45,736 --> 00:56:49,947
The guards on the opposing teams
all remembered to bring their W-2s.

832
00:56:50,032 --> 00:56:54,160
So, Moresby Prison issued you your gun,
but you had to pay for it?

833
00:56:54,244 --> 00:56:55,995
Damn right. The holster, too.

834
00:56:56,080 --> 00:56:57,330
That's tax-deductible.

835
00:56:57,414 --> 00:56:58,581
You can write that off.

836
00:56:58,665 --> 00:57:02,001
RED: Yes, sir.
Andy was a regular cottage industry.

837
00:57:02,086 --> 00:57:05,129
In fact, it got so busy at tax time...

838
00:57:05,214 --> 00:57:07,256
he was allowed a staff.

839
00:57:07,341 --> 00:57:09,801
Hey, Red, can you hand me a stack of 1040s?

840
00:57:09,885 --> 00:57:12,553
It got me out of the wood shop
a month out of the year,

841
00:57:12,638 --> 00:57:15,306
and that was fine by me.

842
00:57:15,390 --> 00:57:18,726
And still...he kept sending those letters.

843
00:57:24,066 --> 00:57:25,900
Red, Andy.

844
00:57:25,984 --> 00:57:27,193
It's Brooks.

845
00:57:27,277 --> 00:57:29,737
(Men shouting)
- Watch the door.

846
00:57:29,822 --> 00:57:31,405
Please, Brooks.

847
00:57:31,490 --> 00:57:33,491
- Just calm the fuck down.
- Stay back!

848
00:57:33,575 --> 00:57:35,618
- Stay back!
- What the hell's going on?

849
00:57:35,702 --> 00:57:38,788
You tell me. One second he's fine.
Then out comes the knife.

850
00:57:38,872 --> 00:57:41,332
Brooks, we can talk about this. Right?

851
00:57:41,416 --> 00:57:43,543
Nothing to talk about, goddamn it!

852
00:57:43,627 --> 00:57:45,336
I'm gonna cut his fucking throat.

853
00:57:45,420 --> 00:57:47,296
Heywood? Wait, what's he done to you?

854
00:57:47,381 --> 00:57:49,507
It's what they done!

855
00:57:49,591 --> 00:57:51,008
I...I got no choice...

856
00:57:51,093 --> 00:57:53,761
You're not gonna hurt him.
Even Heywood knows that.

857
00:57:53,846 --> 00:57:56,472
- Right, Heywood?
- I...I know that, sure.

858
00:57:56,557 --> 00:57:59,976
You won't hurt him, because he's a friend,
and you're a reasonable man.

859
00:58:00,060 --> 00:58:01,352
That's right. Right, guys?

860
00:58:01,436 --> 00:58:04,814
- Yes.
- So, put the knife down. Brooks, look at me.

861
00:58:04,898 --> 00:58:06,691
Put the knife down.

862
00:58:07,818 --> 00:58:08,985
Brooks...

863
00:58:09,069 --> 00:58:11,320
Look at his neck, for God's sake.

864
00:58:11,405 --> 00:58:13,739
Brooks, look at his neck. It's bleeding.

865
00:58:13,824 --> 00:58:14,991
(Heywood gasps)

866
00:58:15,075 --> 00:58:16,659
It's the only...

867
00:58:16,743 --> 00:58:19,036
It's the only way they'd let me stay.

868
00:58:19,121 --> 00:58:21,664
Come on. This is crazy.
You don't want to do this.

869
00:58:21,748 --> 00:58:23,791
Put it down.

870
00:58:25,127 --> 00:58:27,461
(Brooks sobs)

871
00:58:31,175 --> 00:58:35,887
Come on. Take it easy.
You're going to be all right.

872
00:58:35,971 --> 00:58:37,346
HEYWOOD: Him?

873
00:58:37,431 --> 00:58:41,100
Hell, what about me?
Crazy old fool damn near cut my throat.

874
00:58:41,185 --> 00:58:43,811
RED: Shit, Heywood,
you've had worse from shaving.

875
00:58:43,896 --> 00:58:46,147
What the hell did you do to set him off, anyway?

876
00:58:46,231 --> 00:58:48,566
Nothing. I come in here to say fare-thee-well.

877
00:58:48,650 --> 00:58:51,736
Ain't you heard? His parole's come through.

878
00:58:53,822 --> 00:58:56,949
I just don't understand what happened in there.
That's all.

879
00:58:57,034 --> 00:58:59,619
The old man's as crazy
as a rat in a tin shithouse.

880
00:58:59,703 --> 00:59:01,913
Oh, Heywood, that's enough out of you.

881
00:59:01,997 --> 00:59:04,999
- I heard he had you shitting in your pants.
- Fuck you!

882
00:59:05,083 --> 00:59:06,459
Would you knock it off?

883
00:59:06,543 --> 00:59:08,878
Brooks ain't no bug.

884
00:59:08,962 --> 00:59:10,796
He's just...

885
00:59:12,716 --> 00:59:14,508
He's just institutionalised.

886
00:59:15,886 --> 00:59:17,553
Institutionalised, my ass.

887
00:59:17,638 --> 00:59:21,933
The man's been in here 50 years, Heywood.
50 years.

888
00:59:22,017 --> 00:59:23,726
This is all he knows.

889
00:59:23,810 --> 00:59:26,229
In here, he's an important man.

890
00:59:26,313 --> 00:59:27,772
He's an educated man.

891
00:59:27,856 --> 00:59:29,899
Outside, he's nothing.

892
00:59:32,110 --> 00:59:34,737
Just a used-up con with arthritis in both hands.

893
00:59:34,821 --> 00:59:38,032
Probably couldn't get a library card if he tried.

894
00:59:38,116 --> 00:59:40,201
You know what I'm trying to say?

895
00:59:40,285 --> 00:59:43,037
Red, I do believe you're talking out of your ass.

896
00:59:44,289 --> 00:59:47,166
You believe whatever you want, Floyd.

897
00:59:47,251 --> 00:59:49,710
But I'm telling you, these walls are funny.

898
00:59:51,171 --> 00:59:53,214
First you hate 'em...

899
00:59:54,800 --> 00:59:56,842
..then you get used to 'em.

900
00:59:58,512 --> 01:00:01,138
Enough time passes...

901
01:00:01,223 --> 01:00:04,183
you get so you depend on 'em.

902
01:00:04,268 --> 01:00:06,602
That's institutionalised.

903
01:00:06,687 --> 01:00:08,020
JIGGER: Shit.

904
01:00:08,105 --> 01:00:09,689
You can never get like that.

905
01:00:09,773 --> 01:00:11,691
Oh, yeah?

906
01:00:11,775 --> 01:00:14,360
Say that when you've been here
as long as Brooks has.

907
01:00:14,444 --> 01:00:16,279
Goddamn right.

908
01:00:18,657 --> 01:00:21,200
They send you here for life.

909
01:00:21,285 --> 01:00:23,327
That's exactly what they take.

910
01:00:25,289 --> 01:00:27,331
The part that counts, anyway.

911
01:00:30,335 --> 01:00:33,629
(Jake screeches)

912
01:00:34,798 --> 01:00:36,924
I can't take care of you no more, Jake.

913
01:00:38,885 --> 01:00:40,678
You go on, now.

914
01:00:41,805 --> 01:00:46,434
You're free.

915
01:01:02,367 --> 01:01:04,201
Bye.

916
01:01:05,370 --> 01:01:07,204
Good luck, Brooks.

917
01:01:43,825 --> 01:01:46,535
BROOKS: Dear fellas...

918
01:01:46,620 --> 01:01:50,831
I can't believe
how fast things move on the outside.

919
01:01:50,916 --> 01:01:52,166
(Horn blares)

920
01:01:52,250 --> 01:01:55,294
Watch it, old-timer! Are you trying to get killed?

921
01:01:55,379 --> 01:01:58,714
I saw an automobile once, when I was a kid,

922
01:01:58,799 --> 01:02:01,675
but now...they're everywhere.

923
01:02:05,931 --> 01:02:09,475
The world went and got itself
in a big damn hurry.

924
01:02:25,867 --> 01:02:32,164
The parole board got me into
this halfway house called The Brewer,

925
01:02:32,249 --> 01:02:36,043
and a job bagging groceries at the Foodway.

926
01:02:38,088 --> 01:02:43,426
It's hard work, and I try to keep up,
but my hands hurt most of the time.

927
01:02:43,510 --> 01:02:45,511
WOMAN: Make sure your man double-bags.

928
01:02:45,595 --> 01:02:47,847
Last time, the bottom near came out.

929
01:02:47,931 --> 01:02:51,225
Make sure you double-bag, like the lady says.
Understand?

930
01:02:51,309 --> 01:02:52,768
Yes, sir. I surely will.

931
01:02:52,853 --> 01:02:56,647
BROOKS: I don't think
the store manager likes me very much.

932
01:02:56,731 --> 01:02:58,482
(Pigeons cooing)

933
01:02:59,609 --> 01:03:04,405
Sometimes, after work,
I go to the park and feed the birds.

934
01:03:04,489 --> 01:03:09,827
I keep thinking Jake might just show up
and say hello.

935
01:03:09,911 --> 01:03:11,662
But he never does.

936
01:03:12,789 --> 01:03:18,127
And I hope, wherever he is,
he's doing OK and making new friends.

937
01:03:21,673 --> 01:03:24,592
I have trouble sleeping at night.

938
01:03:24,676 --> 01:03:27,428
I have bad dreams, like I'm falling.

939
01:03:28,555 --> 01:03:30,473
I wake up, scared.

940
01:03:30,557 --> 01:03:34,518
Sometimes it takes me a while
to remember where I am.

941
01:03:36,188 --> 01:03:37,646
Maybe I should get me a gun

942
01:03:37,731 --> 01:03:41,609
and rob the Foodway, so they'd send me home.

943
01:03:41,693 --> 01:03:44,028
I could shoot the manager, while I was at it.

944
01:03:44,112 --> 01:03:46,030
Sort of like a bonus.

945
01:03:47,574 --> 01:03:51,827
I guess I'm too old for that sort of nonsense
any more.

946
01:03:51,912 --> 01:03:53,954
I don't like it here.

947
01:03:54,039 --> 01:03:56,707
I'm tired of being afraid all the time.

948
01:03:56,791 --> 01:03:57,875
I've decided...

949
01:03:57,959 --> 01:03:59,793
not to stay.

950
01:04:11,181 --> 01:04:14,683
I doubt they'll kick up any fuss.

951
01:04:14,768 --> 01:04:16,810
Not for an old crook like me.

952
01:04:31,701 --> 01:04:33,577
(Scraping)

953
01:05:19,874 --> 01:05:23,919
"I doubt they'll kick up any fuss.
Not for an old crook like me.

954
01:05:25,088 --> 01:05:29,091
PS. Tell Heywood
I'm sorry I put a knife to his throat.

955
01:05:29,175 --> 01:05:31,218
No hard feelings. Brooks."

956
01:05:41,938 --> 01:05:43,981
He should have died in here.

957
01:05:49,446 --> 01:05:53,866
HADLEY: What the fuck have you done?
It's a goddamn mess. I'll tell you that.

958
01:05:58,622 --> 01:06:00,039
What's all this?

959
01:06:00,123 --> 01:06:04,001
You tell me, fuck-stick.
They're all addressed to you.

960
01:06:04,085 --> 01:06:05,336
Take it.

961
01:06:14,346 --> 01:06:15,888
"Dear Mr Dufresne...

962
01:06:17,015 --> 01:06:19,016
In response to your repeated enquiries,

963
01:06:19,100 --> 01:06:23,812
the State has allocated the enclosed funds
for your library project."

964
01:06:23,897 --> 01:06:25,230
This is 200 dollars.

965
01:06:26,316 --> 01:06:30,235
"In addition, the Library District
has generously responded

966
01:06:30,320 --> 01:06:33,030
with a charitable donation
of used books and sundries.

967
01:06:33,114 --> 01:06:35,199
We trust this will fill your needs.

968
01:06:35,283 --> 01:06:39,411
We now consider the matter closed.
Please stop sending us letters."

969
01:06:39,496 --> 01:06:42,331
I want all this cleared out
before the Warden gets back.

970
01:06:42,415 --> 01:06:44,041
Yes, sir.

971
01:06:47,837 --> 01:06:49,171
Good for you, Andy.

972
01:06:51,841 --> 01:06:53,258
Wow!

973
01:06:54,386 --> 01:06:56,428
It only took six years.

974
01:06:57,806 --> 01:07:00,641
From now on,
I'll write two letters a week, instead of one.

975
01:07:00,725 --> 01:07:04,269
Oh, I believe you're crazy enough.
You'd better get all this stuff out,

976
01:07:04,354 --> 01:07:05,521
like the Captain said.

977
01:07:05,605 --> 01:07:09,441
Now, I'm gonna go pinch a loaf.
When I come back, this is all gone, right?

978
01:07:15,657 --> 01:07:17,616
Wow.

979
01:07:47,731 --> 01:07:50,399
♪ MOZART:
Duettino from The Marriage Of Figaro

980
01:07:51,901 --> 01:07:54,445
♪ Sull'aria...

981
01:07:58,116 --> 01:07:59,116
Andy,

982
01:07:59,200 --> 01:08:00,534
do you hear that?

983
01:08:00,618 --> 01:08:04,288
♪ ..zeffiretto

984
01:08:12,797 --> 01:08:14,590
(Locks door)

985
01:08:16,551 --> 01:08:24,349
♪ Questa sera spirerà

986
01:08:33,109 --> 01:08:34,401
(Feedback hisses)

987
01:08:36,654 --> 01:08:39,531
(Music over loudspeakers)

988
01:08:43,578 --> 01:08:45,621
(Aria continues)

989
01:08:54,798 --> 01:08:59,092
♪ Sotto i pini

990
01:08:59,177 --> 01:09:04,348
♪ Del boschetto

991
01:09:05,892 --> 01:09:08,268
♪ Sotto i pini...

992
01:09:08,353 --> 01:09:11,230
(Banging at door) Dufresne?

993
01:09:11,314 --> 01:09:12,898
Dufresne?

994
01:09:12,982 --> 01:09:15,025
Andy, let me out.

995
01:09:17,779 --> 01:09:21,281
Andy?

996
01:09:21,407 --> 01:09:26,578
RED: I have no idea to this day
what those two Italian ladies were singing about.

997
01:09:26,663 --> 01:09:29,081
The truth is, I don't want to know.

998
01:09:29,165 --> 01:09:31,208
Some things are best left unsaid.

999
01:09:35,296 --> 01:09:40,342
I like to think they were singing about something
so beautiful, it can't be expressed in words...

1000
01:09:40,426 --> 01:09:42,761
and makes your heart ache because of it.

1001
01:09:45,014 --> 01:09:47,724
I tell you, those voices soared...

1002
01:09:47,809 --> 01:09:52,354
higher and farther
than anybody in a grey place dares to dream.

1003
01:09:52,438 --> 01:09:55,816
It was like some beautiful bird
flapped into our drab little cage

1004
01:09:55,900 --> 01:09:59,027
and made those walls dissolve away.

1005
01:09:59,112 --> 01:10:01,446
And for the briefest of moments...

1006
01:10:01,531 --> 01:10:04,575
every last man at Shawshank felt free.

1007
01:10:07,120 --> 01:10:09,580
It pissed the Warden off something awful.

1008
01:10:11,040 --> 01:10:12,124
Open the door.

1009
01:10:14,919 --> 01:10:16,795
Open it up!

1010
01:10:18,047 --> 01:10:20,424
Dufresne, open this door!

1011
01:10:20,508 --> 01:10:21,967
(Bangs door)

1012
01:10:22,051 --> 01:10:23,385
Turn that off!

1013
01:10:23,469 --> 01:10:25,512
(Bangs door)

1014
01:10:27,223 --> 01:10:30,100
(Aria continues)

1015
01:10:30,184 --> 01:10:32,895
I am warning you, Dufresne. Turn that off!

1016
01:10:36,441 --> 01:10:38,483
(Increases volume)

1017
01:10:46,784 --> 01:10:48,619
Dufresne...

1018
01:10:49,787 --> 01:10:51,830
You're mine now.

1019
01:10:59,422 --> 01:11:02,174
RED: Andy got two weeks in the hole
for that little stunt.

1020
01:11:02,258 --> 01:11:04,635
(Hadley stops record) On your feet!

1021
01:11:05,887 --> 01:11:07,930
- Hey, look who's here.
- Maestro!

1022
01:11:09,474 --> 01:11:13,518
Y-Y-You couldn't play something good, huh?
Hank Williams or something?

1023
01:11:13,603 --> 01:11:16,271
They broke the door down
before I could take requests.

1024
01:11:16,356 --> 01:11:18,148
Was it worth it, two weeks in the hole?

1025
01:11:18,232 --> 01:11:19,483
Easiest time I ever did.

1026
01:11:19,567 --> 01:11:22,569
Bullshit!
There's no such thing as easy time in the hole.

1027
01:11:22,654 --> 01:11:25,238
A week in the hole is like a year.

1028
01:11:25,323 --> 01:11:28,033
I had Mr Mozart to keep me company.

1029
01:11:28,117 --> 01:11:31,411
So, they let you tote that record player
down there, huh?

1030
01:11:33,581 --> 01:11:35,207
It was in here.

1031
01:11:35,291 --> 01:11:36,917
And in here.

1032
01:11:38,169 --> 01:11:42,422
That's the beauty of music.
They can't get that from you.

1033
01:11:46,344 --> 01:11:48,804
Haven't you ever felt that way about music?

1034
01:11:50,515 --> 01:11:54,601
Well, I played a mean harmonica,
as a younger man.

1035
01:11:54,686 --> 01:11:56,478
Lost interest in it, though.

1036
01:11:56,562 --> 01:11:58,397
Didn't make much sense in here.

1037
01:11:58,481 --> 01:12:00,941
Here's where it makes the most sense.

1038
01:12:01,025 --> 01:12:03,610
You need it, so you don't forget.

1039
01:12:03,695 --> 01:12:05,028
Forget?

1040
01:12:05,113 --> 01:12:07,072
Forget that...

1041
01:12:07,156 --> 01:12:09,199
there are places...

1042
01:12:10,618 --> 01:12:13,120
..in the world that aren't made out of stone...

1043
01:12:13,204 --> 01:12:15,247
that there's a...

1044
01:12:15,331 --> 01:12:17,165
there's something...

1045
01:12:17,250 --> 01:12:20,043
inside that they can't get to...

1046
01:12:20,128 --> 01:12:22,421
that they can't touch.

1047
01:12:22,505 --> 01:12:24,339
It's yours.

1048
01:12:25,800 --> 01:12:27,467
What are you talking about?

1049
01:12:28,594 --> 01:12:30,178
Hope.

1050
01:12:30,263 --> 01:12:32,097
Hope?

1051
01:12:33,975 --> 01:12:36,643
Let me tell you something, my friend.

1052
01:12:36,728 --> 01:12:38,645
Hope is a dangerous thing.

1053
01:12:40,273 --> 01:12:42,274
Hope can drive a man insane.

1054
01:12:43,359 --> 01:12:45,277
It's got no use on the inside.

1055
01:12:45,361 --> 01:12:47,988
You'd better get used to that idea.

1056
01:12:50,450 --> 01:12:52,034
Like Brooks did?

1057
01:13:17,351 --> 01:13:18,351
Sit down.

1058
01:13:23,608 --> 01:13:27,027
It says here that you've served
30 years of a life sentence.

1059
01:13:27,111 --> 01:13:29,738
You feel you've been rehabilitated?

1060
01:13:29,822 --> 01:13:31,865
Oh, yes, sir.

1061
01:13:31,949 --> 01:13:33,992
Without a doubt.

1062
01:13:35,078 --> 01:13:37,329
And I can honestly say I'm a changed man.

1063
01:13:39,957 --> 01:13:42,000
No danger to society here.

1064
01:13:42,085 --> 01:13:44,127
God's honest truth.

1065
01:13:46,506 --> 01:13:48,548
Absolutely rehabilitated.

1066
01:13:58,518 --> 01:14:00,560
30 years.

1067
01:14:01,687 --> 01:14:03,730
Jesus, when they say it like that...

1068
01:14:03,815 --> 01:14:05,857
You wonder where it went.

1069
01:14:08,861 --> 01:14:10,904
I wonder where ten years went.

1070
01:14:15,993 --> 01:14:17,285
Here.

1071
01:14:17,370 --> 01:14:19,496
Little parole rejection present.

1072
01:14:21,374 --> 01:14:23,416
Go ahead and open it.

1073
01:14:23,501 --> 01:14:27,295
I had to go through one of your competitors.
I hope you don't mind.

1074
01:14:27,380 --> 01:14:29,422
I wanted it to be a surprise.

1075
01:14:39,600 --> 01:14:41,643
It's very pretty, Andy.

1076
01:14:42,770 --> 01:14:44,813
Thank you.

1077
01:14:46,607 --> 01:14:48,650
Are you going to play it?

1078
01:14:52,822 --> 01:14:54,865
No.

1079
01:14:57,201 --> 01:14:59,244
Not right now.

1080
01:15:04,417 --> 01:15:06,459
(Guards shout)

1081
01:15:06,544 --> 01:15:08,587
Tier 3 South. Clear.

1082
01:15:09,672 --> 01:15:11,715
Tier 4 North. Clear.

1083
01:15:11,799 --> 01:15:13,842
Tier 1 South. Clear.

1084
01:15:16,721 --> 01:15:18,763
Fall in!

1085
01:15:21,517 --> 01:15:23,560
(Gate buzzer)

1086
01:15:51,255 --> 01:15:53,298
(Guard's footsteps)

1087
01:15:53,382 --> 01:15:54,966
Lights out!

1088
01:15:55,051 --> 01:15:56,509
(Click of light switches)

1089
01:16:01,974 --> 01:16:04,017
(Guard walks away)

1090
01:16:10,233 --> 01:16:12,275
(Outer door closes)

1091
01:16:21,160 --> 01:16:23,203
(Gently plays one note)

1092
01:16:28,668 --> 01:16:29,793
(Hammering)

1093
01:16:29,877 --> 01:16:31,920
RED: Andy was as good as his word.

1094
01:16:32,004 --> 01:16:34,464
He wrote two letters a week instead of one.

1095
01:16:37,134 --> 01:16:41,263
In 1959, the State Senate
finally clued into the fact

1096
01:16:41,347 --> 01:16:44,182
they couldn't buy him off
with just a $200 cheque.

1097
01:16:44,308 --> 01:16:50,897
Appropriations Committee voted
an annual payment of $500 just to shut him up.

1098
01:16:50,982 --> 01:16:52,691
And you'd be amazed

1099
01:16:52,775 --> 01:16:54,442
how far Andy could stretch it.

1100
01:16:54,527 --> 01:16:57,404
He made deals with book clubs, charity groups.

1101
01:16:57,488 --> 01:16:59,864
He bought remaindered books by the pound.

1102
01:16:59,949 --> 01:17:02,158
Treasure Island.

1103
01:17:02,243 --> 01:17:04,411
Robert Louis...

1104
01:17:04,495 --> 01:17:05,704
..Stevenson.

1105
01:17:05,788 --> 01:17:07,205
Fiction, adventure.

1106
01:17:09,250 --> 01:17:10,834
What's next?

1107
01:17:10,918 --> 01:17:13,545
I got here Auto Repair and...

1108
01:17:14,630 --> 01:17:15,964
..Soap Carving.

1109
01:17:16,048 --> 01:17:19,426
Trade skills and hobbies. Goes under
Educational. The stack behind you.

1110
01:17:19,510 --> 01:17:21,553
The Count Of Monte Crisco.

1111
01:17:21,637 --> 01:17:23,972
That's Cristo, you dumb shit.

1112
01:17:24,056 --> 01:17:27,851
By Alexandree...Dumass.

1113
01:17:27,935 --> 01:17:32,814
Dumb-ass?

1114
01:17:35,359 --> 01:17:37,694
Dumas. You know what that's about?

1115
01:17:37,778 --> 01:17:39,154
Uh-uh.

1116
01:17:39,238 --> 01:17:41,948
You'll like it. It's about a prison break.

1117
01:17:42,033 --> 01:17:46,036
We ought to file that under Educational, too,
oughtn't we?

1118
01:17:46,120 --> 01:17:50,248
RED: The rest of us did our best to pitch in
when and where we could.

1119
01:17:51,542 --> 01:17:53,376
By the year Kennedy was shot,

1120
01:17:53,461 --> 01:17:57,756
Andy had transformed a storage room
smelling of rat turds and turpentine

1121
01:17:57,840 --> 01:18:01,134
into the best prison library in New England,

1122
01:18:01,218 --> 01:18:05,096
complete with a fine selection of Hank Williams.

1123
01:18:05,181 --> 01:18:09,351
♪ Lawd I don't know what I'll do-ooo

1124
01:18:09,435 --> 01:18:12,187
♪ All I do is sit and sigh...

1125
01:18:12,271 --> 01:18:17,025
RED: That was also the year Warden Norton
instituted his famous Inside Out programme.

1126
01:18:17,109 --> 01:18:19,819
You may remember reading about it.

1127
01:18:19,904 --> 01:18:23,323
It made all the papers
and got his picture in Look Magazine.

1128
01:18:23,407 --> 01:18:25,075
No free ride.

1129
01:18:25,159 --> 01:18:28,119
But rather a genuine, progressive advance

1130
01:18:28,204 --> 01:18:30,330
in corrections and rehabilitation.

1131
01:18:31,415 --> 01:18:33,750
Our inmates, properly supervised,

1132
01:18:33,834 --> 01:18:36,586
will be put to work outside these walls,

1133
01:18:36,670 --> 01:18:38,755
performing all manner of public service.

1134
01:18:38,839 --> 01:18:42,759
These men can learn
the value of an honest day's labour,

1135
01:18:42,843 --> 01:18:46,513
while providing a valuable service
to the community and...

1136
01:18:46,597 --> 01:18:51,810
at a bare minimum of expense
to Mr and Mrs John Q Taxpayer.

1137
01:18:51,894 --> 01:18:54,562
RED: Of course,
Norton failed to mention to the press

1138
01:18:54,647 --> 01:18:57,941
that "bare minimum of expense"
is a fairly loose term.

1139
01:18:58,025 --> 01:19:01,194
There are a hundred different ways
to skim off the top.

1140
01:19:01,278 --> 01:19:03,863
Men, materials, you name it.

1141
01:19:04,949 --> 01:19:07,700
And, oh, my Lord, how the money rolled in.

1142
01:19:07,785 --> 01:19:09,911
If this keeps up, you'll put me out of business.

1143
01:19:09,995 --> 01:19:12,163
- Ned!
- This pool of slave labour you've got,

1144
01:19:12,248 --> 01:19:14,290
you can underbid any contractor in town.

1145
01:19:14,375 --> 01:19:18,336
Ned, we're providing
a valuable community service here.

1146
01:19:18,421 --> 01:19:20,672
Well, that's fine for the papers

1147
01:19:20,756 --> 01:19:22,257
but I've got a family to feed.

1148
01:19:22,341 --> 01:19:24,050
Sam...

1149
01:19:24,135 --> 01:19:26,594
Sam, we go back a long way.

1150
01:19:26,679 --> 01:19:29,013
I need this new highway contract.

1151
01:19:29,098 --> 01:19:31,307
I don't get it, and I go under.

1152
01:19:31,392 --> 01:19:33,435
That's a fact.

1153
01:19:33,519 --> 01:19:35,603
You just have some of this fine pie

1154
01:19:35,688 --> 01:19:37,730
my missus made especially for you,

1155
01:19:37,815 --> 01:19:39,107
and you think about that.

1156
01:19:47,199 --> 01:19:50,118
Ned, I wouldn't worry too much
about this contract.

1157
01:19:50,202 --> 01:19:53,371
It seems to me I already got
my boys committed elsewhere.

1158
01:19:55,291 --> 01:19:57,834
You be sure and thank Maisie for this fine pie.

1159
01:19:59,503 --> 01:20:01,671
RED: And behind every shady deal,

1160
01:20:01,755 --> 01:20:03,965
behind every dollar earned,

1161
01:20:04,049 --> 01:20:07,177
there was Andy, keeping the books.

1162
01:20:08,262 --> 01:20:11,681
Two deposits.
Maine National and New England First.

1163
01:20:11,765 --> 01:20:13,808
Night drops as always, sir.

1164
01:20:44,256 --> 01:20:46,007
Get my stuff down to the laundry.

1165
01:20:46,091 --> 01:20:48,885
- Two suits for dry-clean and a bag of whatnot.
- Yes, sir.

1166
01:20:48,969 --> 01:20:52,722
Tell them if they overstarch my shirts again,
they'll hear about it from me.

1167
01:20:52,806 --> 01:20:54,807
How do I look?

1168
01:20:54,892 --> 01:20:57,602
- Very nice, sir.
- Big charity to-do up Portland way.

1169
01:20:57,686 --> 01:20:59,354
The Governor's going to be there.

1170
01:21:00,814 --> 01:21:02,857
Want the rest of this?

1171
01:21:02,942 --> 01:21:04,984
The woman can't bake worth shit.

1172
01:21:06,403 --> 01:21:08,154
Thank you, sir.

1173
01:21:10,366 --> 01:21:14,118
- He's got his fingers in a lot of pies, I hear.
- What you hear isn't half of it.

1174
01:21:14,203 --> 01:21:16,663
He's got scams you haven't even dreamed of.

1175
01:21:16,747 --> 01:21:18,790
Kickbacks on his kickbacks.

1176
01:21:18,874 --> 01:21:21,751
There's a river of dirty money
running through this place.

1177
01:21:21,835 --> 01:21:25,088
But the problem with having all that money
is you'll have to explain

1178
01:21:25,172 --> 01:21:27,757
- where it came from.
- That's where I come in.

1179
01:21:27,841 --> 01:21:30,343
I channel it, filter it, funnel it.

1180
01:21:30,427 --> 01:21:32,971
Stocks, securities, tax-free municipals.

1181
01:21:33,055 --> 01:21:35,723
I send that money out into the real world.

1182
01:21:35,808 --> 01:21:39,435
- And when it comes back...
- Clean as a virgin's honey pot, huh?

1183
01:21:39,520 --> 01:21:40,728
Cleaner.

1184
01:21:40,813 --> 01:21:44,399
By the time Norton retires,
I'll have made him a millionaire.

1185
01:21:47,194 --> 01:21:51,614
If they ever catch on, though, he's gonna
wind up in here wearing a number himself.

1186
01:21:51,699 --> 01:21:54,951
Now, Red, I thought you had
a little more faith in me than that.

1187
01:21:55,035 --> 01:21:58,329
I know you're good, Andy,
but all that paper leaves a trail.

1188
01:21:58,414 --> 01:22:01,416
Now, anybody gets curious,
the FBI, the IRS, whatever,

1189
01:22:01,500 --> 01:22:04,335
it's gonna lead to somebody.

1190
01:22:04,420 --> 01:22:06,379
Sure it is. But not to me.

1191
01:22:06,463 --> 01:22:08,423
And certainly not to the Warden.

1192
01:22:12,511 --> 01:22:13,803
All right. Who?

1193
01:22:13,887 --> 01:22:15,597
Randall Stevens.

1194
01:22:15,681 --> 01:22:16,806
Who?

1195
01:22:17,933 --> 01:22:22,645
The silent silent partner. He's the guilty one,
Your Honour. The man with the bank accounts.

1196
01:22:22,730 --> 01:22:24,897
That's where the filtering process starts.

1197
01:22:24,982 --> 01:22:28,151
If they trace anything,
it's just going to lead to him.

1198
01:22:28,235 --> 01:22:29,819
But who is he?

1199
01:22:29,903 --> 01:22:31,946
He's a phantom, an apparition.

1200
01:22:32,031 --> 01:22:33,990
Second cousin to Harvey the Rabbit.

1201
01:22:34,074 --> 01:22:36,242
I conjured him...

1202
01:22:36,327 --> 01:22:38,369
out of thin air.

1203
01:22:38,454 --> 01:22:41,247
He doesn't exist, except on paper.

1204
01:22:44,418 --> 01:22:46,794
Andy, you can't just make a person up.

1205
01:22:46,879 --> 01:22:50,006
Sure you can, if you know how
the system works, where the cracks are.

1206
01:22:50,090 --> 01:22:53,593
It's amazing what you can accomplish by mail.

1207
01:22:53,677 --> 01:22:56,304
Mr Stevens has a birth certificate,

1208
01:22:56,388 --> 01:22:58,723
a driver's licence, social security number.

1209
01:22:58,807 --> 01:23:00,016
You're shitting me?

1210
01:23:00,100 --> 01:23:02,060
If they ever trace any of those accounts,

1211
01:23:02,144 --> 01:23:05,021
they're going to wind up chasing
a figment of my imagination.

1212
01:23:05,105 --> 01:23:07,148
Well, I'll be damned.

1213
01:23:08,484 --> 01:23:10,526
Did I say you were good?

1214
01:23:10,611 --> 01:23:12,779
Shit, you're a Rembrandt!

1215
01:23:12,863 --> 01:23:14,906
You know, the funny thing is,

1216
01:23:14,990 --> 01:23:18,951
on the outside, I was an honest man,
straight as an arrow.

1217
01:23:20,037 --> 01:23:22,330
I had to come to prison to be a crook.

1218
01:23:31,131 --> 01:23:32,465
Ever bother you?

1219
01:23:33,592 --> 01:23:36,969
I don't run the scams, Red,
I just process the profits.

1220
01:23:37,054 --> 01:23:39,097
Fine line maybe but...

1221
01:23:39,181 --> 01:23:41,891
I also built that library

1222
01:23:41,975 --> 01:23:44,602
and used it to help a dozen guys
get a high school diploma.

1223
01:23:44,687 --> 01:23:46,562
Why do you think the Warden lets me do it?

1224
01:23:46,647 --> 01:23:49,399
To keep you happy and doing the laundry.

1225
01:23:49,483 --> 01:23:51,609
Money instead of sheets.

1226
01:23:51,694 --> 01:23:54,404
Well, I work cheap. That's the trade-off.

1227
01:23:54,488 --> 01:23:56,531
(Siren wails)

1228
01:23:59,993 --> 01:24:02,161
♪ JOHNNY OTIS: Willy And The Hand Jive

1229
01:24:10,003 --> 01:24:11,796
♪ I know a cat named...

1230
01:24:11,880 --> 01:24:14,549
RED: Tommy Williams
came to Shawshank in 1965

1231
01:24:14,633 --> 01:24:16,676
on a two-year stretch for B&E.

1232
01:24:16,760 --> 01:24:18,886
That's breaking and entering to you.

1233
01:24:18,971 --> 01:24:23,599
The cops caught him sneaking TV sets
out the back door of a JC Penney.

1234
01:24:23,684 --> 01:24:25,435
Young punk.

1235
01:24:25,519 --> 01:24:27,562
Mr Rock'n'roll.

1236
01:24:27,646 --> 01:24:29,313
Cocky as hell.

1237
01:24:29,398 --> 01:24:31,983
Hey, come on, old boys! Moving like molasses!

1238
01:24:32,067 --> 01:24:33,985
Making me look bad.

1239
01:24:34,069 --> 01:24:35,987
RED: We liked him immediately.

1240
01:24:36,071 --> 01:24:38,114
So I'm backing out the door, right?

1241
01:24:38,198 --> 01:24:39,907
And I got the TV like this.

1242
01:24:39,992 --> 01:24:43,828
It was a big old thing. I couldn't see shit.
Suddenly, I hear this voice.

1243
01:24:43,912 --> 01:24:45,955
"Freeze, kid! Hands in the air."

1244
01:24:46,039 --> 01:24:47,707
Well, I just stand there,

1245
01:24:47,791 --> 01:24:50,585
holding onto that TV. So, finally, the voice says,

1246
01:24:50,669 --> 01:24:52,628
"Do you hear what I said, boy?"

1247
01:24:52,713 --> 01:24:55,089
I say, "Yes, sir, I sure did.

1248
01:24:55,174 --> 01:24:58,801
But if I drop this fucking thing,
you got me on destruction of property, too."

1249
01:24:58,886 --> 01:25:00,970
(Laughter)

1250
01:25:02,890 --> 01:25:05,600
Hey, you've done a stretch in Cashman, right?

1251
01:25:05,684 --> 01:25:09,520
Yeah. Yeah, that was an easy piece of time,
let me tell you.

1252
01:25:09,605 --> 01:25:12,231
Weekend furloughs, work programmes.

1253
01:25:12,316 --> 01:25:13,733
Not like here.

1254
01:25:13,817 --> 01:25:16,152
Sounds like you done time
all over New England.

1255
01:25:16,236 --> 01:25:21,324
Yeah, I've been in and out since I was 13. You
name the place, chances are I've been there.

1256
01:25:21,408 --> 01:25:25,411
Perhaps it's time you tried a new profession?

1257
01:25:25,496 --> 01:25:30,583
What I mean is, you don't seem to be a good
thief. Maybe you should try something else.

1258
01:25:30,667 --> 01:25:34,504
Yeah, well, what the hell
do you know about it, Capone?

1259
01:25:34,588 --> 01:25:36,339
What are you in for?

1260
01:25:36,423 --> 01:25:38,007
Me?

