01:42:45,326 --> 01:42:49,037
I just didn't expect
the storm would last as long as it has.

1514
01:42:53,167 --> 01:42:55,043
Do you think you'll ever get out of here?

1515
01:42:56,337 --> 01:42:57,963
Me?

1516
01:43:00,299 --> 01:43:01,716
Yeah.

1517
01:43:02,802 --> 01:43:04,719
One day, when I've got a long, white beard

1518
01:43:04,846 --> 01:43:08,306
and two or three marbles rolling around upstairs,
they'll let me out.

1519
01:43:10,268 --> 01:43:12,310
I tell you where I'd go.

1520
01:43:13,563 --> 01:43:15,188
Zihuatanejo.

1521
01:43:15,273 --> 01:43:17,190
Zi...what?

1522
01:43:17,275 --> 01:43:19,317
Zihuatanejo.

1523
01:43:19,402 --> 01:43:21,444
It's in Mexico.

1524
01:43:23,281 --> 01:43:25,448
A little place on the Pacific Ocean.

1525
01:43:26,742 --> 01:43:29,119
You know what the Mexicans say
about the Pacific?

1526
01:43:29,203 --> 01:43:30,662
No.

1527
01:43:30,746 --> 01:43:32,789
They say it has no memory.

1528
01:43:35,293 --> 01:43:37,794
That's where I want to live the rest of my life.

1529
01:43:39,422 --> 01:43:41,464
A warm place with no memory.

1530
01:43:44,802 --> 01:43:47,053
Open up a little hotel,

1531
01:43:48,931 --> 01:43:50,807
right on the beach.

1532
01:43:50,892 --> 01:43:52,934
Buy some worthless old boat,

1533
01:43:53,019 --> 01:43:55,061
fix it up new.

1534
01:43:58,065 --> 01:43:59,274
Take my guests out.

1535
01:43:59,358 --> 01:44:01,401
Charter fishing.

1536
01:44:05,364 --> 01:44:07,949
Zihuatanejo, huh?

1537
01:44:10,620 --> 01:44:14,456
In a place like that, I could use a man
who knows how to get things.

1538
01:44:20,922 --> 01:44:23,590
I don't think I could make it on the outside, Andy.

1539
01:44:30,389 --> 01:44:32,432
I've been in here most of my life.

1540
01:44:33,976 --> 01:44:35,769
I'm an institutional man now.

1541
01:44:35,853 --> 01:44:37,896
Just like Brooks was.

1542
01:44:39,357 --> 01:44:41,608
Well, you underestimate yourself.

1543
01:44:41,692 --> 01:44:43,735
I don't think so.

1544
01:44:46,405 --> 01:44:50,617
I mean...in here, I'm the guy
who can get things for you, sure.

1545
01:44:50,701 --> 01:44:54,621
But outside, all you need is the Yellow Pages.

1546
01:44:54,705 --> 01:44:57,082
Hell, I wouldn't even know where to begin.

1547
01:44:59,210 --> 01:45:01,544
The Pacific Ocean?

1548
01:45:01,629 --> 01:45:03,672
Shit.

1549
01:45:03,756 --> 01:45:06,925
- About scare me to death, something that big.
- Not me.

1550
01:45:07,009 --> 01:45:10,428
I didn't shoot my wife and I didn't shoot her lover.

1551
01:45:12,390 --> 01:45:16,017
Whatever mistakes I've made,
I've paid for them and then some.

1552
01:45:16,102 --> 01:45:18,228
That hotel, that boat.

1553
01:45:19,855 --> 01:45:21,982
I don't think that's too much to ask.

1554
01:45:26,654 --> 01:45:29,531
I don't think you ought to be
doing this to yourself, Andy.

1555
01:45:29,615 --> 01:45:31,658
These are just shitty pipe dreams.

1556
01:45:31,742 --> 01:45:34,703
I mean, Mexico is way the hell down there
and you're in here.

1557
01:45:34,787 --> 01:45:36,830
And that's the way it is.

1558
01:45:36,914 --> 01:45:39,499
Yeah, right. That's the way it is.

1559
01:45:41,293 --> 01:45:43,336
It's down there and I'm in here.

1560
01:45:46,090 --> 01:45:48,842
I guess it comes down to a simple choice, really.

1561
01:45:51,721 --> 01:45:53,763
Get busy living

1562
01:45:53,848 --> 01:45:56,725
or get busy dying.

1563
01:46:00,563 --> 01:46:02,605
Andy.

1564
01:46:05,109 --> 01:46:07,152
Red.

1565
01:46:08,237 --> 01:46:10,655
If you ever get out of here, do me a favour.

1566
01:46:10,740 --> 01:46:12,574
Sure, Andy.

1567
01:46:12,658 --> 01:46:13,950
Anything.

1568
01:46:15,077 --> 01:46:18,496
There's a big hayfield up near Buxton.
You know where Buxton is?

1569
01:46:20,541 --> 01:46:24,335
- Well, just... There's a lot of hayfields up there.
- One in particular.

1570
01:46:24,420 --> 01:46:26,463
It's got a long rock wall

1571
01:46:26,547 --> 01:46:28,465
with a big oak tree at the north end.

1572
01:46:28,549 --> 01:46:31,217
It's like something out of a Robert Frost poem.

1573
01:46:32,636 --> 01:46:35,305
It's where I asked my wife to marry me.

1574
01:46:36,557 --> 01:46:40,351
We went there for a picnic
and made love under that oak.

1575
01:46:41,854 --> 01:46:43,897
I asked and she said yes.

1576
01:46:48,069 --> 01:46:50,111
Promise me, Red,

1577
01:46:50,196 --> 01:46:52,197
if you ever get out,

1578
01:46:52,281 --> 01:46:54,282
find that spot.

1579
01:46:55,367 --> 01:47:00,830
At the base of that wall, you'll find a rock that has
no earthly business in a Maine hayfield.

1580
01:47:00,915 --> 01:47:03,374
A piece of black, volcanic glass.

1581
01:47:06,587 --> 01:47:09,380
There's something buried under it
I want you to have.

1582
01:47:09,465 --> 01:47:11,466
What, Andy?

1583
01:47:11,550 --> 01:47:13,593
What's buried under there?

1584
01:47:15,429 --> 01:47:18,765
You'll have to pry it up to see.

1585
01:47:24,188 --> 01:47:26,231
No, I'm telling you, the guy is...

1586
01:47:27,316 --> 01:47:29,359
He's talking funnier.

1587
01:47:29,443 --> 01:47:32,821
- I'm really worried about him.
- We ought to keep an eye on him.

1588
01:47:32,905 --> 01:47:36,908
That's fine during the day,
but at night he's got that cell all to himself.

1589
01:47:38,035 --> 01:47:39,494
Oh, Lord.

1590
01:47:39,578 --> 01:47:41,579
What?

1591
01:47:43,290 --> 01:47:45,625
Andy come down to the loading dock today.

1592
01:47:45,709 --> 01:47:49,212
- He asked me for a length of rope.
- Rope?

1593
01:47:49,296 --> 01:47:51,131
Six feet long.

1594
01:47:51,215 --> 01:47:52,674
And you gave it to him?

1595
01:47:52,758 --> 01:47:55,385
Sure I did. Why wouldn't I?

1596
01:47:55,469 --> 01:47:57,137
Jesus, Heywood.

1597
01:47:57,221 --> 01:47:59,472
Hey, how the hell was I supposed to know?

1598
01:47:59,557 --> 01:48:01,474
Remember Brooks Hatlen?

1599
01:48:01,559 --> 01:48:02,559
No.

1600
01:48:03,644 --> 01:48:05,812
Andy would never do that.

1601
01:48:05,896 --> 01:48:07,939
Never.

1602
01:48:09,024 --> 01:48:11,067
I don't know.

1603
01:48:13,112 --> 01:48:15,155
Every man has his breaking point.

1604
01:48:17,825 --> 01:48:19,075
Lickety-split.

1605
01:48:19,160 --> 01:48:21,995
- I want to get home.
- Just about finished, sir.

1606
01:48:38,137 --> 01:48:40,180
Three deposits tonight.

1607
01:48:48,606 --> 01:48:50,648
Get my stuff down to the laundry.

1608
01:48:50,733 --> 01:48:54,152
And shine my shoes.
I want 'em looking like mirrors.

1609
01:48:54,236 --> 01:48:55,570
Yes, sir.

1610
01:49:00,910 --> 01:49:02,577
It's good having you back, Andy.

1611
01:49:02,661 --> 01:49:05,371
The place wasn't the same without you.

1612
01:49:07,541 --> 01:49:09,584
(Whistles)

1613
01:49:52,461 --> 01:49:55,171
GUARD: Lights out!
(Click of light switches)

1614
01:49:59,551 --> 01:50:01,594
(Footsteps)

1615
01:50:07,476 --> 01:50:09,519
(Outer door closes)

1616
01:50:25,953 --> 01:50:28,204
RED: I've had some long nights in stir.

1617
01:50:29,290 --> 01:50:32,000
Alone in the dark with nothing but your thoughts,

1618
01:50:32,084 --> 01:50:33,876
time can draw out like a blade.

1619
01:50:33,961 --> 01:50:36,004
(Thunder rumbles)

1620
01:50:40,301 --> 01:50:42,593
That was the longest night of my life.

1621
01:50:52,855 --> 01:50:55,148
(Gate buzzer)

1622
01:50:58,777 --> 01:51:00,361
GUARD: Give me a count.

1623
01:51:04,742 --> 01:51:06,784
Tier 3 South. Clear.

1624
01:51:06,869 --> 01:51:08,202
Tier 4 North. Clear.

1625
01:51:08,287 --> 01:51:11,873
- Tier 3 North. Clear.
- Man missing on Tier 2.

1626
01:51:11,957 --> 01:51:15,043
- Cell 245.
- Dufresne.

1627
01:51:15,127 --> 01:51:18,004
Get your ass out here, boy.
You're holding up the show.

1628
01:51:20,549 --> 01:51:24,552
Don't make me come down there.
I'll thump your skull for you.

1629
01:51:32,186 --> 01:51:35,563
Damn it, Dufresne, you're putting me behind!
I got a schedule to keep.

1630
01:51:35,647 --> 01:51:38,733
You'd better be sick or dead in there,
I shit you not!

1631
01:51:38,817 --> 01:51:40,610
You hear me?

1632
01:51:47,159 --> 01:51:49,202
Oh, my holy God.

1633
01:52:01,340 --> 01:52:03,383
(Siren wails)

1634
01:52:06,095 --> 01:52:08,763
I want every man on this cell block questioned.

1635
01:52:08,847 --> 01:52:11,015
- Start with that friend of his.
- Who?

1636
01:52:11,100 --> 01:52:12,266
Him!

1637
01:52:14,228 --> 01:52:16,270
Open 237.

1638
01:52:19,316 --> 01:52:21,442
What do you mean, he just wasn't here?

1639
01:52:21,527 --> 01:52:23,069
Don't say that to me, Haig.

1640
01:52:23,153 --> 01:52:25,405
Don't say that to me again.

1641
01:52:25,489 --> 01:52:26,572
But, sir, he wasn't.

1642
01:52:26,657 --> 01:52:28,825
I can see that, Haig!

1643
01:52:28,909 --> 01:52:30,660
You think I'm blind?

1644
01:52:30,744 --> 01:52:33,830
Is that what you're saying? Am I blind, Haig?

1645
01:52:33,914 --> 01:52:34,914
No, sir.

1646
01:52:34,998 --> 01:52:37,041
What about you?

1647
01:52:37,126 --> 01:52:38,960
Are you blind?

1648
01:52:39,044 --> 01:52:41,587
- Tell me what this is.
- Last night's count.

1649
01:52:41,672 --> 01:52:44,966
You see Dufresne's name there?
I sure do. See? Right there.

1650
01:52:45,050 --> 01:52:46,884
Dufresne.

1651
01:52:48,178 --> 01:52:49,846
He was in his cell at lights out.

1652
01:52:49,930 --> 01:52:53,099
It stands to reason
he'd still be here in the morning.

1653
01:52:54,226 --> 01:52:56,102
I want him found.

1654
01:52:56,186 --> 01:52:58,771
Not tomorrow, not after breakfast.

1655
01:52:58,856 --> 01:52:59,856
Now!

1656
01:52:59,940 --> 01:53:01,357
Yes, sir!

1657
01:53:02,526 --> 01:53:05,111
Let's go, let's go!
Move your butts! Move it!

1658
01:53:07,948 --> 01:53:08,948
Stand.

1659
01:53:10,117 --> 01:53:11,367
Well?

1660
01:53:14,746 --> 01:53:15,872
Well, what?

1661
01:53:15,956 --> 01:53:19,375
I see you two all the time.
You're thick as thieves, you are.

1662
01:53:20,461 --> 01:53:22,086
He must have said something.

1663
01:53:22,171 --> 01:53:24,213
No, sir, Warden.

1664
01:53:24,298 --> 01:53:25,715
Not a word.

1665
01:53:27,759 --> 01:53:29,719
Lord, it's a miracle!

1666
01:53:30,804 --> 01:53:33,264
A man up and vanished like a fart in the wind.

1667
01:53:33,348 --> 01:53:35,099
Nothing left but...

1668
01:53:35,184 --> 01:53:38,102
some damn rocks on a windowsill.

1669
01:53:38,187 --> 01:53:39,937
And that cupcake on the wall.

1670
01:53:40,022 --> 01:53:41,647
Let's ask her.

1671
01:53:41,732 --> 01:53:45,651
Maybe she knows. What say there,
Fuzzy Britches? Feel like talking?

1672
01:53:46,778 --> 01:53:47,820
Ah...

1673
01:53:47,905 --> 01:53:49,322
I guess not.

1674
01:53:49,406 --> 01:53:52,283
Why should she be any different?

1675
01:53:52,367 --> 01:53:54,827
This is a conspiracy.

1676
01:53:54,912 --> 01:53:57,121
That's what this is.

1677
01:53:57,206 --> 01:53:58,748
One big...

1678
01:53:58,832 --> 01:54:01,584
damn conspiracy!

1679
01:54:01,668 --> 01:54:04,337
And everyone's in on it!

1680
01:54:04,421 --> 01:54:05,671
Including her!

1681
01:54:07,049 --> 01:54:08,674
(Clattering)

1682
01:54:32,491 --> 01:54:34,158
(Sirens blare)

1683
01:54:40,374 --> 01:54:42,250
RED: In 1966,

1684
01:54:42,334 --> 01:54:45,002
Andy Dufresne escaped

1685
01:54:45,087 --> 01:54:47,129
from Shawshank Prison.

1686
01:54:48,840 --> 01:54:51,592
All they found of him
was a muddy set of prison clothes,

1687
01:54:51,677 --> 01:54:53,719
a bar of soap

1688
01:54:53,804 --> 01:54:58,140
and an old rock hammer
damn near worn down to the nub.

1689
01:55:02,563 --> 01:55:07,400
I remember thinking it would take a man
600 years to tunnel through the wall with it.

1690
01:55:07,484 --> 01:55:10,152
Old Andy did it in less than 20.

1691
01:55:28,755 --> 01:55:30,798
Oh, Andy loved geology.

1692
01:55:31,883 --> 01:55:35,386
I imagine it appealed to his meticulous nature.

1693
01:55:35,470 --> 01:55:37,763
An Ice Age here,

1694
01:55:37,848 --> 01:55:40,391
a million years of mountain-building there.

1695
01:55:41,476 --> 01:55:43,853
Geology is the study of pressure and time.

1696
01:55:45,105 --> 01:55:47,148
That's all it takes, really.

1697
01:55:47,232 --> 01:55:49,275
Pressure...

1698
01:55:49,359 --> 01:55:51,235
and time.

1699
01:55:51,320 --> 01:55:54,614
That and a big goddamn poster.

1700
01:55:55,741 --> 01:55:57,783
(Coughing)

1701
01:55:57,868 --> 01:55:59,201
Like I said,

1702
01:55:59,286 --> 01:56:02,997
in prison, a man will do most anything
to keep his mind occupied.

1703
01:56:05,834 --> 01:56:11,005
It turns out Andy's favourite hobby
was toting his wall out into the exercise yard.

1704
01:56:11,089 --> 01:56:13,132
A handful at a time.

1705
01:56:15,010 --> 01:56:17,178
I guess after Tommy was killed,

1706
01:56:17,262 --> 01:56:20,097
Andy decided he'd been here
just about long enough.

1707
01:56:20,182 --> 01:56:22,350
Lickety-split. I want to get home.

1708
01:56:23,685 --> 01:56:25,728
I'm just about finished, sir.

1709
01:56:47,167 --> 01:56:49,210
Three deposits tonight.

1710
01:56:56,426 --> 01:56:58,427
Andy did like he was told.

1711
01:56:59,513 --> 01:57:02,973
Buffed those shoes to a high mirror shine.

1712
01:57:06,603 --> 01:57:08,646
The guard simply didn't notice.

1713
01:57:08,730 --> 01:57:10,773
Neither did I.

1714
01:57:10,857 --> 01:57:15,152
I mean, seriously, how often
do you really look at a man's shoes?

1715
01:57:49,896 --> 01:57:51,939
(Thunderclap)

1716
01:59:19,236 --> 01:59:25,407
Andy crawled to freedom through 500 yards
of shit-smelling foulness I can't even imagine.

1717
01:59:25,492 --> 01:59:26,659
(Gags)

1718
01:59:26,743 --> 01:59:28,744
Or maybe I just don't want to.

1719
01:59:28,829 --> 01:59:30,871
(Coughs and spits)

1720
01:59:33,458 --> 01:59:35,626
500 yards.

1721
01:59:36,711 --> 01:59:39,171
That's the length of five football fields.

1722
01:59:40,257 --> 01:59:42,466
Just shy of half a mile.

1723
02:00:24,050 --> 02:00:25,718
(Laughs)

1724
02:00:37,731 --> 02:00:42,276
The next morning, right about the time
Raquel was spilling her little secret,

1725
02:00:42,360 --> 02:00:45,779
a man nobody ever laid eyes on before

1726
02:00:45,864 --> 02:00:48,282
strode into the Maine National Bank.

1727
02:00:48,366 --> 02:00:50,409
Until that moment,

1728
02:00:50,493 --> 02:00:52,369
he didn't exist,

1729
02:00:52,454 --> 02:00:53,787
except on paper.

1730
02:00:53,872 --> 02:00:54,914
May I help you?

1731
02:00:54,998 --> 02:00:57,041
RED: He had all the proper ID,

1732
02:00:57,125 --> 02:01:00,753
driver's licence, birth certificate,
social security card.

1733
02:01:00,837 --> 02:01:04,131
And the signature was a spot-on match.

1734
02:01:04,215 --> 02:01:07,259
I must say, I'm sorry to be losing your business.

1735
02:01:07,344 --> 02:01:09,345
I hope you'll enjoy living abroad.

1736
02:01:09,429 --> 02:01:11,221
Thank you.

1737
02:01:11,306 --> 02:01:13,098
I'm sure I will.

1738
02:01:13,183 --> 02:01:15,309
Here's your cashier's cheque, sir.

1739
02:01:15,393 --> 02:01:17,436
Will there be anything else?

1740
02:01:17,520 --> 02:01:18,520
Please...

1741
02:01:18,605 --> 02:01:21,690
Would you add this to your outgoing mail?

1742
02:01:21,775 --> 02:01:23,984
I'd be happy to.

1743
02:01:24,069 --> 02:01:26,362
- Good day, sir.
- Good day.

1744
02:01:26,488 --> 02:01:31,241
RED: Mr Stevens visited nearly a dozen banks
in the Portland area that morning.

1745
02:01:32,452 --> 02:01:38,916
All told, he blew town with better than $370,000
of Warden Norton's money.

1746
02:01:39,000 --> 02:01:41,460
Severance pay for 19 years.

1747
02:01:41,544 --> 02:01:43,587
(Phone rings)

1748
02:01:49,594 --> 02:01:51,845
Good morning, Portland Daily Bugle.

1749
02:01:59,562 --> 02:02:01,605
(Sirens wail)

1750
02:02:30,844 --> 02:02:32,845
(Sirens approaching)

1751
02:02:44,607 --> 02:02:47,568
Byron Hadley?
You have the right to remain silent.

1752
02:02:47,694 --> 02:02:52,322
If you give up the right to remain silent, anything
you say will be held against you in court.

1753
02:02:52,407 --> 02:02:54,283
RED: I wasn't there to see it.

1754
02:02:54,367 --> 02:02:59,204
But I hear Byron Hadley started sobbing
like a little girl when they took him away.

1755
02:03:04,669 --> 02:03:07,421
Norton had no intention of going that quietly.

1756
02:03:23,480 --> 02:03:24,897
Samuel Norton?

1757
02:03:24,981 --> 02:03:28,192
- We have a warrant for your arrest. Open up.
(Banging on door)

1758
02:03:31,112 --> 02:03:32,237
Norton!

1759
02:03:32,322 --> 02:03:33,989
Open the door.

1760
02:03:34,074 --> 02:03:35,783
I'm not sure which key it is.

1761
02:03:38,703 --> 02:03:40,329
Norton!

1762
02:03:45,835 --> 02:03:47,878
Make it easy on yourself, Norton.

1763
02:03:59,224 --> 02:04:02,810
RED: I like to think
the last thing that went through his head,

1764
02:04:02,894 --> 02:04:04,603
other than that bullet,

1765
02:04:04,687 --> 02:04:08,649
was to wonder how the hell
Andy Dufresne ever got the best of him.

1766
02:04:10,360 --> 02:04:11,443
Carter, James...

1767
02:04:11,528 --> 02:04:14,905
RED: Not long after the Warden
deprived us of his company,

1768
02:04:14,989 --> 02:04:17,199
I got a postcard in the mail.

1769
02:04:18,952 --> 02:04:21,370
It was blank but the postmark said...

1770
02:04:21,454 --> 02:04:24,206
Fort Hancock, Texas.

1771
02:04:24,290 --> 02:04:26,333
Fort Hancock.

1772
02:04:26,417 --> 02:04:28,460
Right on the border.

1773
02:04:28,545 --> 02:04:30,587
That's where Andy crossed.

1774
02:04:30,672 --> 02:04:34,508
When I picture him heading south
in his own car with the top down,

1775
02:04:35,593 --> 02:04:37,636
it always makes me laugh.

1776
02:04:39,097 --> 02:04:41,140
Andy Dufresne,

1777
02:04:41,224 --> 02:04:43,600
who crawled through a river of shit

1778
02:04:43,685 --> 02:04:45,727
and came out clean on the other side.

1779
02:04:46,980 --> 02:04:49,022
Andy Dufresne,

1780
02:04:49,107 --> 02:04:51,024
headed for the Pacific.

1781
02:04:53,611 --> 02:04:55,654
Hadley's got him by the toes, right?

1782
02:04:55,738 --> 02:04:59,950
And he says, "I believe this boy's
about to have himself an accident."

1783
02:05:00,034 --> 02:05:03,203
RED: Those of us who knew him best
talk about him often.

1784
02:05:03,288 --> 02:05:05,539
I swear, the stuff he pulled...

1785
02:05:05,623 --> 02:05:08,125
"These friends of mine
could use a couple of beers!"

1786
02:05:08,209 --> 02:05:10,252
- And he got it.
- And he got it!

1787
02:05:11,462 --> 02:05:13,839
RED: Sometimes it makes me sad, though,

1788
02:05:13,923 --> 02:05:15,966
Andy being gone.

1789
02:05:16,050 --> 02:05:20,012
I have to remind myself
that some birds aren't meant to be caged.

1790
02:05:21,139 --> 02:05:23,182
Their feathers are just too bright.

1791
02:05:24,767 --> 02:05:26,810
And when they fly away,

1792
02:05:26,895 --> 02:05:30,772
the part of you that knows
it was a sin to lock them up does rejoice.

1793
02:05:32,567 --> 02:05:34,026
But still...

1794
02:05:34,110 --> 02:05:38,238
the place you live in is that much more drab
and empty that they're gone.

1795
02:05:42,827 --> 02:05:45,037
I guess I just miss my friend.

1796
02:06:09,062 --> 02:06:10,896
Please sit down.

1797
02:06:16,527 --> 02:06:18,654
Ellis Boyd Redding.

1798
02:06:18,738 --> 02:06:22,115
Your files say you've served
40 years of a life sentence.

1799
02:06:22,200 --> 02:06:24,534
Do you feel you've been rehabilitated?

1800
02:06:26,704 --> 02:06:28,747
Rehabilitated?

1801
02:06:30,333 --> 02:06:32,376
Well, now, let me see.

1802
02:06:33,461 --> 02:06:35,754
You know, I don't have any idea
what that means.

1803
02:06:37,590 --> 02:06:40,133
Well, it means you're ready to rejoin society...

1804
02:06:40,218 --> 02:06:42,719
I know what you think it means, sonny.

1805
02:06:45,139 --> 02:06:47,182
To me, it's just a made-up word.

1806
02:06:48,268 --> 02:06:50,519
A politician's word so that...

1807
02:06:50,603 --> 02:06:56,066
young fellas like yourself
can wear a suit and a tie and have a job.

1808
02:06:58,528 --> 02:07:00,570
What do you really want to know?

1809
02:07:01,781 --> 02:07:03,699
Am I sorry for what I did?

1810
02:07:03,783 --> 02:07:05,450
Well, are you?

1811
02:07:07,120 --> 02:07:09,663
There's not a day goes by I don't feel regret.

1812
02:07:11,291 --> 02:07:14,376
Not because I'm in here
or because you think I should.

1813
02:07:18,214 --> 02:07:20,257
I look back on the way I was then.

1814
02:07:22,885 --> 02:07:24,928
A young...

1815
02:07:25,013 --> 02:07:28,056
stupid kid who committed that terrible crime.

1816
02:07:31,936 --> 02:07:33,979
I wanna talk to him.

1817
02:07:35,398 --> 02:07:37,524
I wanna try and talk some sense to him,

1818
02:07:38,609 --> 02:07:40,652
tell him the way things are.

1819
02:07:42,864 --> 02:07:44,906
But I can't.

1820
02:07:46,159 --> 02:07:48,201
That kid's long gone.

1821
02:07:49,537 --> 02:07:51,580
This old man is all that's left.

1822
02:07:53,750 --> 02:07:55,208
I gotta live with that.

1823
02:07:56,586 --> 02:07:58,378
Rehabilitated?

1824
02:07:58,463 --> 02:08:00,464
It's just a bullshit word.

1825
02:08:00,548 --> 02:08:06,428
So you go on and stamp your form, sonny,
and stop wasting my time.

1826
02:08:07,555 --> 02:08:09,598
Because to tell you the truth,

1827
02:08:09,682 --> 02:08:12,142
I don't give a shit.

1828
02:08:50,306 --> 02:08:52,349
(Gate closes)

1829
02:09:11,786 --> 02:09:13,829
(Siren passes outside)

1830
02:09:38,396 --> 02:09:40,439
Here you go, miss.

1831
02:09:42,483 --> 02:09:43,900
Rest room break, boss?

1832
02:09:49,991 --> 02:09:54,244
You don't need to ask me every time you need
to go take a piss. Just go. Understand?

1833
02:09:55,496 --> 02:09:57,122
Yes, sir.

1834
02:10:07,216 --> 02:10:10,218
RED: 40 years
I've been asking permission to piss.

1835
02:10:11,262 --> 02:10:13,430
I can't squeeze a drop without say-so.

1836
02:10:17,602 --> 02:10:19,644
There's a harsh truth to face.

1837
02:10:21,647 --> 02:10:23,940
No way I'm gonna make it on the outside.

1838
02:10:32,200 --> 02:10:35,619
All I do any more
is think of ways to break my parole...

1839
02:10:36,704 --> 02:10:38,747
..so maybe they'd send me back.

1840
02:10:44,295 --> 02:10:46,338
A terrible thing to live in fear.

1841
02:10:47,757 --> 02:10:51,092
Brooks Hatlen knew it, knew it all too well.

1842
02:10:53,304 --> 02:10:56,056
All I want is to be back
where things make sense,

1843
02:10:57,141 --> 02:10:59,601
where I won't have to be afraid all the time.

1844
02:11:02,522 --> 02:11:04,564
Only one thing stops me.

1845
02:11:05,650 --> 02:11:07,692
A promise I made to Andy.

1846
02:11:28,464 --> 02:11:30,507
Here it is.

1847
02:11:40,351 --> 02:11:42,394
Much obliged, sir.

1848
02:15:05,681 --> 02:15:07,724
(Bird calls)

1849
02:15:21,238 --> 02:15:22,530
ANDY: Dear Red,

1850
02:15:22,615 --> 02:15:25,074
if you're reading this, you've gotten out.

1851
02:15:25,159 --> 02:15:29,412
And if you've come this far,
maybe you're willing to come a little further.

1852
02:15:29,497 --> 02:15:32,040
You remember the name of the town, don't you?

1853
02:15:34,418 --> 02:15:36,461
Zihuatanejo.

1854
02:15:37,546 --> 02:15:38,713
I could use a good man

1855
02:15:38,798 --> 02:15:40,840
to help me get my project on wheels.

1856
02:15:40,925 --> 02:15:43,051
I'll keep an eye out for you

1857
02:15:43,135 --> 02:15:45,136
and the chessboard ready.

1858
02:15:46,222 --> 02:15:47,597
Remember, Red,

1859
02:15:47,681 --> 02:15:49,724
hope is a good thing.

1860
02:15:49,809 --> 02:15:51,851
Maybe the best of things.

1861
02:15:51,936 --> 02:15:53,978
And no good thing ever dies.

1862
02:15:55,064 --> 02:15:57,524
I will be hoping that this letter finds you

1863
02:15:57,608 --> 02:15:59,651
and finds you well.

1864
02:15:59,735 --> 02:16:02,195
Your friend, Andy.

1865
02:16:36,814 --> 02:16:40,650
RED: Get busy living or get busy dying.

1866
02:16:43,237 --> 02:16:45,280
That's goddamn right.

1867
02:16:50,786 --> 02:16:52,912
For the second time in my life,

1868
02:16:52,997 --> 02:16:55,039
I'm guilty of committing a crime.

1869
02:16:56,750 --> 02:16:58,793
Parole violation.

1870
02:16:58,878 --> 02:17:02,505
Of course, I doubt they'll toss up
any roadblocks for that.

1871
02:17:03,799 --> 02:17:05,842
Not for an old crook like me.

1872
02:17:05,926 --> 02:17:07,969
Fort Hancock, Texas, please.

1873
02:17:11,724 --> 02:17:15,810
I find I'm so excited I can barely sit still
or hold a thought in my head.

1874
02:17:16,896 --> 02:17:19,898
I think it's the excitement
only a free man can feel.

1875
02:17:19,982 --> 02:17:22,692
A free man at the start of a long journey

1876
02:17:22,776 --> 02:17:25,653
whose conclusion is uncertain.

1877
02:17:28,574 --> 02:17:30,700
I hope I can make it across the border.

1878
02:17:32,620 --> 02:17:35,371
I hope to see my friend and shake his hand.

1879
02:17:37,791 --> 02:17:40,960
I hope the Pacific is as blue
as it has been in my dreams.

1880
02:17:43,756 --> 02:17:45,590
I hope.



